Throughout the 1960s, Brzezinski was an advisor to John F. Kennedy and later the Lyndon B. Johnson administration.
During the 1976 elections, he advised Carter on foreign policy and then served as National Security Advisor (NSA) from 1977 to 1981, taking over from Henry Kissinger.
As a member of the NSA, he collaborated with Carter on the diplomatic management of international affairs, including the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between China and the United States in the late 1970s, the Iranian revolution (which led to the Iran hostage crisis in 1979) and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
