This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely held, but provides greater detail than fossils, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
. According to what scientists say, the plumage of this animal was chestnut brown in the upper part, with a pale or carotenoid color in the lower part.
The discovery also allows us to obtain detailed information about the evolution of bird feathers.
Since the dinosaur's plumage does not have the basic structure, the so-called rachis, but instead has other typical characteristics of feathers, barbs and barbules, the researchers concluded that the rachis is probably the result of an evolutionary development subsequent to these characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that it was not used for flight, but rather for temperature regulation or courtship. The researchers hypothesize that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the find shows adult plumage and not chick down.
According to the researchers' hypotheses, although the tail belongs to a young dinosaur, the sample reveals the plumage of an adult specimen and not that of a chick.
